# UI Theme Compatibility

For user-facing UI work, ensure visuals and states remain usable in **all four** theme modes:

1. Light
2. Dark
3. High Contrast Light (WCAG AAA, request #37 Tier 2)
4. High Contrast Dark (WCAG AAA, request #37 Tier 2)

## Implementation guidance

- Never hardcode one-theme-only colors for text, backgrounds, borders, focus rings, or state highlights. Always read from `ShellThemeTokens`.
- Prefer semantic, theme-aware tokens that map cleanly across all four themes.
- Maintain readable contrast for normal, hover, selected, disabled, warning, and error states.
- Use `tokens.focus_border_width` for focus-state border widths so HC modes (which set `focus_border_width=2`) get visibly thicker focus rings without per-mode branching.
- Ensure icons, badges, and status indicators stay recognizable on every surface. SVG icons colored from `tokens.icon_primary` / `tokens.icon_muted` inherit HC tuning automatically.

## Validation expectations

- When UI code changes, verify affected views in **all four** theme modes (Light, Dark, HC Light, HC Dark) before considering the task complete.
- HC Light targets pure-white (`#FFFFFF`) editor/panel backgrounds with body text contrast >= 7:1 (WCAG AAA). HC Dark targets pure-black (`#000000`).
- If full four-theme validation cannot be run, explicitly note the gap in the completion summary and call out which themes were verified.
